# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hsqldb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] An **embedded database** system is a database management system (DBMS) that is tightly integrated with application software, and is embedded within the application rather than provided as a standalone system.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] The term “embedded” is sometimes used to refer to use on embedded devices (as opposed to the definition given above).
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] However, only a small subset of embedded database systems are used in real-time embedded systems such as telecommunications switches and consumer electronics.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Advantage Database Server (ADS) is an embedded database management system developed by Sybase.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It provides both Indexed Sequential Access Method (ISAM) and relational data access and is compatible with multiple platforms, including Windows, Linux, and Netware.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It is available as a royalty-free local file-server database or as a full client-server system.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Apache Derby is an embeddable SQL database engine written entirely in Java.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It is fully transactional and supports multi-user access, and is available under the Apache license.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It is also distributed as part of Oracle's Java SE Development Kit (JDK) under the name of Java DB.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Empress Embedded Database was developed by Empress Software, Inc., a privately held company founded in 1979.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It is a relational database management system that has been embedded in a range of applications, including medical systems, network routers, nuclear power plant monitors, and satellite management systems.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Empress is an ACID-compliant, SQL database engine with APIs for C, C++, Java, JDBC, ODBC, SQL, ADO.NET, and kernel-level APIs.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Applications developed using these APIs can be run in standalone or client-server modes.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Empress Embedded Database runs on Linux, Unix, Microsoft Windows, and real-time operating systems.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Extensible Storage Engine (ESE) is an ISAM data storage technology developed by Microsoft.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It serves as a core component of Microsoft Exchange Server and Active Directory, allowing applications to store and retrieve data using indexed and sequential access.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] ESE is also used by Windows Mail and Desktop Search in Windows Vista to store indexes and property information, respectively.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] eXtremeDB, launched by McObject LLC as an in-memory embedded database, was designed specifically for real-time embedded systems.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] The initial product was later joined by eXtremeDB High Availability (HA) for fault-tolerant applications.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] The eXtremeDB family now includes 64-bit and transaction logging editions, as well as the hybrid eXtremeDB Fusion, which combines in-memory and on-disk data storage.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] In 2008, McObject introduced eXtremeDB Kernel Mode, an embedded DBMS designed to run in an operating system kernel.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] eXtremeDB is used in real-time and embedded systems worldwide.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] McObject also offers Perst, an open source, object-oriented embedded database for Java, Java ME, .NET, .NET Compact Framework, and Silverlight.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Firebird Embedded is a relational database engine and an open-source fork of InterBase.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It is ACID-compliant, supports triggers and stored procedures, and is available on Linux, macOS, and Windows.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It has the same features as the Classic and SuperServer versions of Firebird.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Starting with Firebird 2.5, two or more threads or applications can access the same database simultaneously.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Firebird Embedded acts as a local server for one-threaded client accessing its databases.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] For example, this allows ASP.NET web applications to work properly, because each user runs in a separate thread, so two users can access the same database at the same time without a conflict.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Firebird Embedded exports the standard Firebird API entry points.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Unlike SQLite or Access databases, Firebird Embedded databases can be moved to a full Firebird server without modification and are multi-platform, running on Linux and macOS with full ASP.NET Mono support.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Although it can operate within an application process, Firebird is not truly embedded because it cannot be statically linked.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] H2 is an open-source database engine written in Java.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It supports both embedded and server modes, as well as clustering, and can run within the Google App Engine environment.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It supports encrypted database files using AES or XTEA.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Development of H2 began in May 2004, and it was first published on December 14, 2005.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] H2 is dual-licensed and is available under a modified version of the Mozilla Public License (MPL) or the unmodified Eclipse Public License (EPL) 1.0.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] HailDB is a standalone, embeddable form of the InnoDB Storage Engine.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Because it is based on the same codebase as InnoDB, it includes many of the same features, such as high performance and scalability, multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), row-level locking, deadlock detection, fault tolerance, and automatic crash recovery.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] As an embedded engine independent of MySQL, HailDB does not include server components such as networking or object-level permissions.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] By eliminating MySQL server overhead, it has a relatively small footprint and is well suited for embedding in applications that require high performance and concurrency.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] As with many embedded database systems, HailDB is designed to be accessed primarily through an ISAM-like C API rather than SQL, although a limited SQL variant is supported.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] The project is no longer maintained as of 2015.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] HSQLDB is an open-source relational database management system with a BSD-like license that runs within the same Java Virtual Machine as the embedded application.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It supports a variety of in-memory and disk-based table modes, Unicode, and SQL:2016.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] InfinityDB is a sorted, hierarchical key-value store.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It is available in encrypted and client-server editions.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] The database provides transactional support, data compression, and operates within a single file, enabling simplified deployment and minimal administration.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] APIs include the ItemSpace interface, a ConcurrentNavigableMap view, and support for JSON.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] The RemoteItemSpace component can redirect embedded API calls to other database instances.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] The client-server edition includes a lightweight servlet server, web-based administration and database browsing tools, and REST support for Python.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Informix Dynamic Server (IDS) is an enterprise-class, embeddable database server that combines features such as low footprint, programmability, and autonomic capabilities with enterprise database features including high availability and flexible replication.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] IDS is used in embedded scenarios such as IP telephony call-processing systems, point-of-sale applications, and financial transaction processing systems.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] InterBase is a cross-platform, Unicode-enabled SQL database that can be embedded within turn-key applications.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It supports symmetric multiprocessing (SMP), on-disk AES-256 encryption, SQL-92 compliance, and ACID properties, and is available on Windows, macOS, Linux, Solaris, iOS, and Android platforms.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] InterBase is used in both small- to medium-sized and large enterprise environments, supporting multi-user and mobile application development.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] *InterBase Light* is a free version designed for mobile devices and is suitable for mobile applications.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Organizations can upgrade to a paid version as requirements for features such as change management and security increase.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] InterBase has been adopted in industries including defense, airspace, oil and gas, and manufacturing.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Kùzu is an embeddable graph database management system that supports the Cypher query language.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It implements a range of existing and novel state-of-art storage, indexing, and query processing techniques to support the management and querying of large graphs.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Kùzu achieves its performance through a combination of join algorithms, including binary and worst-case optimal joins, as well as factorization and vectorized query execution on a columnar storage layer, along with compression and parallelization techniques common in modern database systems.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Kùzu is developed and maintained by Kùzu Inc., a startup based in Waterloo, Ontario, Canada, and is available as open-source software under the MIT license.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] LevelDB is an ordered key-value store created by Google as a compact implementation of the Bigtable storage design.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It is provided as a library, with a native API in C++.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It also includes official C wrappers for most functionality, and third-party wrappers are available for languages such as Python, PHP, Go, Node.js, and Objective C.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Google distributes LevelDB under the New BSD License.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Lightning Memory-Mapped Database (LMDB) is a memory-mapped key-value database developed for the OpenLDAP Project.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It is written in C, and its API is modeled after the Berkeley DB API, but simplified.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] The library is compact, typically compiling to under 40 KB of x86 object code.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] LMDB implements B+ trees with multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), a single-level store, copy-on-write, and provides full ACID transactions without deadlocks.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It is optimized for high read concurrency: readers require no locks, readers do not block writers, and writers do not block readers, allowing read performance to scale linearly across multiple threads and CPUs.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Third-party wrappers are available for C++, Erlang and Python.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] LMDB is distributed under the OpenLDAP Public License.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] As of 2013, the OpenLDAP Project has deprecated the use of Berkeley DB in favor of LMDB.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Mimer SQL is a proprietary relational database server.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] An embedded, zero-maintenance version is available, featuring a small footprint due to its modular design, full support for the SQL standard, and ports to Windows, Linux, Automotive Grade Linux, Android, QNX, INTEGRITY, and other platforms.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] MonetDB/e is the embedded version of the open-source MonetDB SQL column store engine.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It is available for C, C++, Java (JDBC), and Python, and is distributed under the MonetDB License, based on MPL 2.0.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Its predecessor, MonetDBLite (for R, Python, and Java), is no longer maintained and has been replaced by MonetDB/e.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] The Embedded MySQL Server Library provides most of the features of the standard MySQL server as a linkable library that runs within the context of a client process.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] After initialization, clients can use the same C API calls as when communicating with a separate MySQL server, but with lower communication overhead and without the need for a separate database process.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] NexusDB is the commercial successor to the FlashFiler database, which is now open source.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Both databases can be embedded in Delphi applications to create stand-alone executables with full database functionality.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] ObjectDB is an object database for Java that can be used in either client-server mode or embedded (in process) mode.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Oracle's embedded database is Berkeley DB, which Oracle acquired from Sleepycat Software.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Berkeley DB was originally developed at the University of California.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It is a fast, open-source embedded database and is used in several well-known open-source products, including the Linux and BSD Unix operating systems, the Apache Web server, and the OpenOffice productivity suite.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] In recent years, some projects have switched to using Lightning Memory-Mapped Database (LMDB), citing better performance in key scenarios and a simpler "less is more" design, as well as changes to Berkeley DB's licensing.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] RocksDB was created by Facebook as a fork of LevelDB.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It focuses on performance, particularly on solid-state drives (SSDs), and adds a range of features, including transactions, backups, snapshots, bloom filters, column families, expiry, custom merge operators, more tunable compaction, statistics collection, and geospatial indexing.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It is used as a storage engine inside of several other databases, including ArangoDB, Ceph, CockroachDB, MyRocks, Rocksandra, TiKV, and YugabyteDB.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] solid DB is a hybrid on-disk/in-memory, relational database often used as an embedded system database in telecommunications equipment, network software, and similar applications.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] Its in-memory technology enables throughput of tens of thousands of transactions per second with response times measured in microseconds.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] A high-availability option maintains two synchronized copies of the data.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] In the event of a system failure, applications can recover access to solidDB in less than a second without data loss.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] SQLite is a software library that provides a self-contained, serverless, zero-configuration, transactional SQL database engine.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It is the most widely deployed SQL database engine in the world.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] The source code, written primarily in C, is in the public domain.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] SQLite includes both a native C library and a simple command-line client for managing its database.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It is included in several operating systems, including Android, FreeBSD, iOS, macOS, and Windows 10, and is also used by the Chromium web browser and its derivatives.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] SQL Server Compact is an embedded database by Microsoft with features including multi-process connections, T-SQL, ADO.NET Sync Services for synchronizing with back-end databases, Merge Replication with SQL Server, and programming APIs such as LINQ to SQL, LINQ to Entities, and ADO.NET.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] The product runs on both desktop and mobile Windows platforms.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] It has been in production software over a long period.
[src:hsqldb/embedded-database] SQL Server Compact has undergone multiple rebrandings and has been known by various names, including SQL CE, SQL Server CE, SQL Server Mobile, and SQL Mobile.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Since the release of version 2.0, many new features and enhancements have been introduced in point releases.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Regular code reviews, user feedback, and bug fixes resulted in the latest release.
[src:hsqldb/features200] This document lists the enhancements and new features in version 2.0 and beyond.
[src:hsqldb/features200] An extensive range of new SQL and JDBC capabilities, increased scalability, and better query optimisation have been achieved by a rewrite of most of the internal components and the addition of some major new ones.
[src:hsqldb/features200] All areas of functionality have been thoroughly tested with an extensive internal test suite and by users with their applications.
[src:hsqldb/features200] HyperSQL 2.0 went into alpha release in April 2009 and several RC releases were downloaded over 20000 times before the final release in June 2010.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Over 200 users submitted bug reports which were promptly fixed.
[src:hsqldb/features200] The same process was repeated again and again over the next 9 years.
[src:hsqldb/features200] There were 7 point releases in 2011, followed by another 16 between 2012 and 2024.
[src:hsqldb/features200] An extensive Guide was written over two years to cover all features of the engine in detail.
[src:hsqldb/features200] It has been updated with each release to cover the latest features.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Fully multithreaded core supports 2PL (two-phased locking) and MVCC (multiversion concurrency control), plus a hybrid 2PL+MVCC transaction control mode.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Transactions can be SERIALIZABLE or READ COMMITTED, using strict 2PL concurrency control.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Version 2.0 also adds the MVCC modes, SNAPSHOT ISOLATION and READ CONSISTENCY, which are comparable to REPEATABLE READS and READ COMMITTED isolation levels, but with higher concurrency.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Many enhancements are introduced to allow maximum multi-threaded concurrency in different isolation modes.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Massive high performance LOB store for BLOBs and CLOBs up to multi-gigabyte size, with total storage capacity of 64 terabytes.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Increased default storage space of 64GB for all CACHED table disk-based data, with fast startup and shutdown.
[src:hsqldb/features200] The default can always be extended to 8TB with a connection property.
[src:hsqldb/features200] With another connection property at the time of database creation, the maximum can be extended to 256TB.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Large result sets, views and subqueries can now be stored on disk (on the server side) while being generated and accessed.
[src:hsqldb/features200] The threshold to store a result on disk, as well as the actual fetch size in client-server configurations can be specified per connection.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Internal and external commands for backing up databases to TAR and GZIP archives.
[src:hsqldb/features200] All query conditions, whether in a JOIN or WHERE clause, are now allocated to an index if possible.
[src:hsqldb/features200] IN queries are now optimised to use an index if possible.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Conditions with OR are optimised if indexes can be used.
[src:hsqldb/features200] MAX(), MIN() and ORDER BY with or without LIMIT and OFFSET expressions can use indexes.
[src:hsqldb/features200] All indexes can be used in reverse order for these operations.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Indexes on multiple columns are used efficiently.
[src:hsqldb/features200] All subquery and view access is optimised.
[src:hsqldb/features200] HyperSQL supports schema-based stored procedures and functions written entirely in SQL.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Procedural SQL language includes WHILE loops, IF, CASE WHEN, and exception handling statements.
[src:hsqldb/features200] SQL procedures can return multiple result sets and return values.
[src:hsqldb/features200] SQL functions can return single values, arrays, or tables that can be used in SQL queries.
[src:hsqldb/features200] User defined aggregate functions written in SQL are supported.
[src:hsqldb/features200] HyperSQL supports schema-based stored procedures and functions written entirely in JAVA.
[src:hsqldb/features200] User defined aggregate functions are supported.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Java procedures can return multiple result sets and return values.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Java functions can can return single values, arrays or even tables that can be used in SQL queries.
[src:hsqldb/features200] HyperSQL supports system-versioned tables, which keep all update history.
[src:hsqldb/features200] This feature can be used with the new log-based synchronization capability to keep replicated databases in sync.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Support for BIT, BIT VARYING, CLOB, BLOB, INTERVAL according to the SQL Standards.
[src:hsqldb/features200] TIME can now have a fractional second part.
[src:hsqldb/features200] TIME WITH TIME ZONE and TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE are supported.
[src:hsqldb/features200] The full range of combinations of datetime and interval types is supported.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Support for DOMAIN objects with constraints and DISTINCT types.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Arrays of most types can be used in table definitions, expressions, function parameters and return types.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Multiple collations can be used for different tables or columns.
[src:hsqldb/features200] A collation can be specified for ORDER BY.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Complete rewrite of scanner and parser classes.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports all SQL standard identifier and character string literals (Unicode strings and escapes, etc.).
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports extended CASE WHEN conditions such as CASE X WHEN IN (,,), BETWEEN A AND B, 21, 56, IS NULL THEN ..
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports Z BETWEEN [SYMMETRIC | ASYMMETRIC] (X, Y) predicate.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports (A,B,C) MATCHES [UNIQUE] [SIMPLE]|[PARTIAL]|[FULL] (SELECT …) predicates.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Full Standard syntax and semantics (arithmetic and other operations) of expressions involving INTERVAL types.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports type casts to INTERVAL types modifiers (e.g. <expression> DAY).
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports WITH TIME ZONE data types, including zone modifiers (i.e. <expression> AT LOCAL | AT TIME ZONE …).
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports standard SQL grammar, including IS [NOT] {NULL | TRUE | FALSE | UNKNOWN}.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports expressions in all LIKE arguments.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Both INSERT and UPDATE command have been enhanced to support multi-row inserts, omission of parentheses, DEFAULT keyword, mix of subquery and row expressions.
[src:hsqldb/features200] The powerful MERGE command is fully supported.
[src:hsqldb/features200] MERGE statement with full Standard compliant syntax is supported.
[src:hsqldb/features200] SELECT has been extensively enhanced, supporting all Standard join types.
[src:hsqldb/features200] The scope of column labels in SELECT queries is now treated according to the SQL Standard.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports TABLE X to introduce the equivalent of SELECT * FROM TABLE X in set operations.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports VALUES (,,,), (,,,) as table constructor in joins.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports TABLE, LATERAL and UNNEST table constructor in joins.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports WITH RECURSIVE for named subqueries allowing recursive queries.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports column name list after correlation name SELECT ..
[src:hsqldb/features200] JOIN conditions can now contain any valid boolean expressions.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Full support for inclusion of set functions (e.g.
[src:hsqldb/features200] COUNT, AVG) in subquery conditions contained within a HAVING clause.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Includes support for user-defined aggregate functions.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports FETCH <row count> ROWS ONLY as SQL Standard alternative to LIMIT at the end of query expression.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports full set of SEQUENCE generator options ([NO] MAXVALUE, [NO] MINVALUE, [NO] CYCLE, etc.) and data types including SMALLINT, INT, BIGINT, DECIMAL, NUMERIC.
[src:hsqldb/features200] These are supported in IDENTITY sequences and in normal sequences, including all relevant ALTER COLUMN and ALTER SEQUENCE commands.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports GENERATED {BY DEFAULT | ALWAYS} AS IDENTITY in a different column than the PRIMARY KEY column.
[src:hsqldb/features200] A user supplied value or a value returned from a SELECT statement can always be inserted into an identity column.
[src:hsqldb/features200] If GENERATED ALWAYS has been specified, then OVERRIDING SYSTEM VALUE must be included in the INSERT statement.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports GENERATED ALWAYS AS <expression> for derivative columns that are based on other column values.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Extended CREATE SCHEMA …. statements can include cross references between FOREIGN KEY constraints in different tables.
[src:hsqldb/features200] CREATE TABLE can have mixed column and constraint creation elements.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Similarly, ALTER TABLE … ADD COLUMN can feature constraint definitions.
[src:hsqldb/features200] ALTER TABLE … ALTER COLUMN … SET DATA TYPE … supported.
[src:hsqldb/features200] DROP COLUMN and ALTER TABLE … DROP CONSTRAINT.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Named NOT NULL constraints now supported in column definition CONSTRAINT C NOT NULL.
[src:hsqldb/features200] All NOT NULL constraints are treated as CHECK (C IS NOT NULL) type constraints and listed as such in system tables.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports VIEW definitions including tables and sequences in other schemas.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports CREATE SYNONYM for tables, sequences and routines.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Full set of SQL Standard functions, including correct type handling and application to all supported types (e.g.
[src:hsqldb/features200] SUBSTRING for character (CHAR, VARCHAR, CLOB) and binary (BINARY, VARBINARY, BLOB) types.
[src:hsqldb/features200] TO_CHAR, TO_DATE, TRUNCATE, GROUP_CONCAT, ARRAY_AGG REGXP_MATCHES, REGXP_SUBSTRING, REGX_SUBSTRING_ARRAY DECODE, GREATEST, etc.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Full set of SQL JSON constructor functions allows building JSON objects with nested elements using SELECT statements.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports column level SELECT, INSERT and UPDATE access rights, with GRANT and REVOKE on individual columns of tables, including WITH GRANT OPTION.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports SQL STATE with messages defined by the standard.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports several syntax and operation compatibility flags to ease testing and porting applications written against a different database engine.
[src:hsqldb/features200] These include PostgreSQL, MySQL, Oracle, MS SQL Server and DB2.
[src:hsqldb/features200] New compatibility features have been added in each point release.
[src:hsqldb/features200] The latest version 2.7 is highly compatible with those databases.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Even some of the most non-standard syntax constructs such as ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE are now supported.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports getGeneratedKeys() calls in Statement and PreparedStatement.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports POSIX functions TIMESTAMPDIFF and TIMESTAMPADD.
[src:hsqldb/features200] All applicable new methods are supported.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Import and export of comma-separated text files as well as SQL data and definition scripts are supported.
[src:hsqldb/features200] The JDBCPool class offers a fast and simple connection pool dedicated to HSQLDB.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports and implements DataSource, PooledConnection, ConnectionPoolDataSource, XADataSource and XAResource interfaces.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports SQL Standard INFORMATION SCHEMA views, together with additional views used in JDBC.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Standard views are supported correctly and reflect the user's permissions on database objects.
[src:hsqldb/features200] The Server now supports remote opening of databases.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports advanced external user authentication and password complexity checks.
[src:hsqldb/features200] Supports SQL statement logging as well as external framework logging via Log4J and JRE logging.
[src:hsqldb/features200] SQL-92 direct SQL is supported fully to Advanced Level except for deferrable constraint enforcement, ASSERTION, and CHECK constraints that contain subqueries.
[src:hsqldb/features200] All SQL:2003 - SQL:2023 Standard CORE features are supported.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] Version 2.7.4 of HyperSQL Database adds features from the latest SQL:2023 standard, including ANY_VALUE and LISTAGG aggregate functions and CAST with templates.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] Zip package at the download link above contains Java 11 module jars and Java 8 jars for HSQLDB and SQL Tool.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] HSQLDB (HyperSQL DataBase) is the leading SQL relational database system written in Java.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] It offers a small, fast multithreaded and transactional database engine with in-memory and disk-based tables and supports embedded and server modes.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] HSQLDB supports the widest range of SQL Standard features seen in any open source database engine: SQL:2023 core language features and an extensive list of SQL:2023 optional features.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] It supports full Advanced ANSI-92 SQL with only two exceptions.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] Many extensions to the Standard, including syntax compatibility modes and features of other popular database engines, are also supported.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] HyperSQL is fully multithreaded and supports high performance 2PL and MVCC (multiversion concurrency control) transaction control models.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] See the list of features in the latest version.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] Recent releases added support for JSON constructor functions as well as direct CSV data load and unload.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] Temporal system-versioned tables keep all the data changes over time, allowing queries to view historic snapshots and, with PERIOD predicates, data changes over any period of time.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] Fine-grained row-level access control governs visibility and permissions on rows of data.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] Log-based synchronization keeps replicas in sync.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] Support for Java 8 java.time classes in JDBC, table spaces for disk-based tables, UUID type for columns, SYNONYM for tables and functions, and auto-updated TIMESTAMP columns on row updates, are some of the recent features.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] Other features include: The ability to cancel long-running statements from JDBC as well as from admin sessions.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] UTF-16 file support for text table sources.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] MySQL compatibility for REPLACE, INSERT IGNORE and ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE statements.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] HSQLDB has been constantly developed for over 20 years and is used as a database and persistence engine in over 1700 Open Source Software projects and many commercial products.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] The latest versions are extremely stable and reliable.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] It is known for its small size, ability to execute completely or partly in memory, its flexibility and speed.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb-org] HSQLDB is completely free to use and distribute under our licenses, based on the standard BSD license and fully compatible with all major open source licenses.
