[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] It is used as a database and persistence engine in many open source software projects, such as descendants of OpenOffice.org Base (i.e., Apache OpenOffice Base, LibreOffice Base, etc.), and the Jitsi VoIP and video-conference client since version 2.6.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] It is also used in commercial products, such as Mathematica and InstallAnywhere (starting with version 8.0).
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] HSQLDB version 2.0 has three transaction control modes.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] It supports read committed and serializable transaction isolation levels with table level locks or with multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), or a combination of locks and MVCC.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] Version 1.8.1 supports transaction isolation level 0 (read uncommitted) only.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] HSQLDB has two main table types used for durable read-write data storage, i.e., if a transaction has been successfully committed, it is guaranteed that the data will survive system failure and will keep their integrity.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] The default MEMORY type stores all data changes to the disk in the form of a SQL script.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] During engine start-up, these commands are executed and data are reconstructed into the memory.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] Another table type is CACHED, which allows one to store more data, at the cost of the slower performance.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] The HSQLDB engine loads them only partially and synchronizes the data to the disk on transaction commits.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] However, the engine always loads all rows affected during an update into the memory.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] This renders very large updates impossible without splitting the work into smaller parts.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] Other table types allow access to comma-separated values (CSV) files.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] These tables can participate, for example, in queries with JOINs and simplify spreadsheet processing and read-write non-durable in-memory data storage.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] HSQLDB 2.0 supports all the core features and many optional features of SQL:2008.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] Advanced features include user-defined SQL procedures and functions, schemas, datetime intervals, updatable views, arrays, lobs, full and lateral joins and set operations.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] Many non-standard functions such as TO_CHAR and DECODE are also supported.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] Extensions to standard SQL include user-defined aggregate functions.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] Several versions of HSQLDB have been released since 2001.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] Early versions were based on the discontinued HypersonicSQL database engine.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] Version 2.0, released in 2010, is mostly new code, written to conform to Standard SQL and JDBC 4 Specification.
[src:hsqldb/hsqldb] Version 2.3.2 (released in 2014) is fully multi-threaded and supports high performance two-phase locking and MVCC (multiversion concurrency control) transaction control models.
